  <Placemark>
    <name>King's Highway - Camino Real - Old San Antonio Road</name>
    <description><![CDATA[Old Bastrop Highway (CR 266), N side, 0.3 mi. NE of York Creek Rd. Close to Comal-Hays county line. Pink granite marker 76 of 128 placed in 1918.<br/><br/><b>Address:</b> Old Bastrop Highway, New Braunfels<br/><br/><b>Marker Text:</b> King's Highway - Camino Real - Old San Antonio Road. Marked by the Daughters of the American Revolution and the State of Texas A.D. 1918]]></description>
    <Point><coordinates>-97.967334,29.813265,0</coordinates></Point>
  </Placemark>
  <Placemark>
    <name>Koch Cemetery</name>
    <description><![CDATA[32368 Bulverde Dr in Bulverde Estates<br/><br/><b>Address:</b> 32368 Bulverde Dr, Bulverde<br/><br/><b>Marker Text:</b> Koch Cemetery Established 1874 Historic Texas Cemetery - 2004]]></description>
    <Point><coordinates>-98.442702,29.756077,0</coordinates></Point>
  </Placemark>
  <Placemark>
    <name>Mission Hill</name>
    <description><![CDATA[2100 Independence Dr. | thc:Latitude/Longitude is a general geocoded approximation from the street address (US Census geocoder), not field-verified.<br/><br/><b>Address:</b> 2100 Independence Dr., New Braunfels<br/><br/><b>Marker Text:</b> The highest point in the city of New Braunfels, this site is long believed to be important to Native American and Spanish interests. It is unknown if there was a mission on the exact site, although the name was associated with this hill by the 1840s. In 1856, German immigrants Friedrich Ludwig Hermann (F.L.H.) and Georgine Conring purchased the land. During the Civil War, Ernst Conring operated a saltpeter kiln. In 1883, the Conrings sold the land to Franz and Minna Coreth. In the 140 years the Coreth family owned the property, they built significant homes on the property and engaged in goat, sheep and cattle ranching. Mission Hill recalls early activity and settlement in the area. (2023)]]></description>
    <Point><coordinates>-98.163307,29.712557,0</coordinates></Point>
  </Placemark>
  <Placemark>
    <name>Mission Valley School</name>
    <description><![CDATA[<b>Address:</b> 1135 Mission Valley Rd., New Braunfels<br/><br/><b>Marker Text:</b> German settlers established the Mission Valley community, named for an earlier Spanish mission, in the mid-1840s. Area families educated their children in their homes before brothers Karl and Julius Brehmer donated land for the first community school in 1870. Trustees built a frame schoolhouse, and in 1884 a larger limestone school was built on land acquired from Friedrich and Emilie Heidrich; the frame school then became a teacherage. New Braunfels Independent School District annexed Mission Valley in 1952. Since that time this site, which includes the historic frame and stone schoolhouses, stone cisterns and other features, has served as a community center. Recorded Texas Historic Landmark - 2009]]></description>
    <Point><coordinates>-98.201113,29.722507,0</coordinates></Point>
  </Placemark>
  <Placemark>
    <name>Old Lex Homestead</name>
    <description><![CDATA[at site, 26 mi. NW of New Braunfels, off FM 475, on Old Blanco Road<br/><br/><b>Address:</b> 33561 Blanco Road, New Braunfels<br/><br/><b>Marker Text:</b> Built 1873-74 by Peter Lex (1849-1921), German-born pioneer, and wife Carolina. All rock in the original structure was hand-cut and faced. This story-and-half limestone farm cottage is typical of German houses of te Texas Hill county. RTHL - 1969]]></description>
    <Point><coordinates>-98.541013,29.781821,0</coordinates></Point>
  </Placemark>
  <Placemark>
    <name>Old Schmidt Home</name>
    <description><![CDATA[354 W Bridge St., New Braunfels<br/><br/><b>Address:</b> 354 W. Bridge Street, New Braunfels<br/><br/><b>Marker Text:</b> Built 1850s of adobe, hand-hewn cedar, pine, oak. Has pitched roof, outside stair. Story and half. "Fachwerk" style. Recorded Texas Historic Landmark--1968]]></description>
    <Point><coordinates>-98.128691,29.701826,0</coordinates></Point>
  </Placemark>
  <Placemark>
    <name>Pantermuel House</name>
    <description><![CDATA[17 mi. NW of New Braunfels, off CR 311<br/><br/><b>Address:</b> 485 Bremer Rd., Canyon Lake<br/><br/><b>Marker Text:</b> Pioneer home of Heimrich Pantermuehl (1842 - 1921) and wife Pauline, German-born settlers of Comal County. Built about 1865, its use of limestone and native cedar is typical of small German farm cottages of this area. RTHL - 1972]]></description>
    <Point><coordinates>-98.328168,29.799917,0</coordinates></Point>
  </Placemark>
  <Placemark>
    <name>Posey Cemetery</name>
    <description><![CDATA[<b>Address:</b> 1275 Soechting Lane, New Braunfels]]></description>
    <Point><coordinates>-98.010866,29.768382,0</coordinates></Point>
  </Placemark>
  <Placemark>
    <name>Richard E. and Ella Sodke Kloepper House</name>
    <description><![CDATA[<b>Address:</b> 492 E. Main St., New Braunfels<br/><br/><b>Marker Text:</b> Texas native Richard E. Kloepper and Ella Sodke married in 1906, the same year construction began on this house. A prominent local businessman, Richard was a founding member of New Braunfels State Bank, and of the local First Federal Savings and Loan Association. The couple moved from the house with their only son, Kermit, in 1911. A subsequent owner was Albert Voss, whose family lived here for many years. The Queen Anne home, built of longleaf pine, retains much of its original detailing, including porch spindle frieze, decorative shingling, and a bracketed window hood on the front projecting wing.Recorded Texas Historic Landmark-2003]]></description>
    <Point><coordinates>-98.116386,29.712732,0</coordinates></Point>
  </Placemark>
  <Placemark>
    <name>Schoenthal School</name>
    <description><![CDATA[RT 3009, 0.7 mi. north of Gardenridge<br/><br/><b>Address:</b> 23145 FM 3009, Garden Ridge<br/><br/><b>Marker Text:</b> Incorporated into the present structure is the Schoenthal School, built in 1872. A late example of the German fachwerk style of architecture. (1972) Incise on base: Erected by Mr. and Mrs. W. N. Deason, Jr. and family.]]></description>
    <Point><coordinates>-98.30496,29.656155,0</coordinates></Point>
  </Placemark>
  <Placemark>
    <name>St. Joseph's Cemetery</name>
    <description><![CDATA[approximately 7 miles southwest of downtown New Braunfels on FM 482, one hundred yards south of Bunker Street<br/><br/><b>Address:</b> 6510 FM 482, New Braunfels<br/><br/><b>Marker Text:</b> HTC Medallion only]]></description>
    <Point><coordinates>-98.2026,29.657314,0</coordinates></Point>
