    <Point><coordinates>-98.322467,29.963258,0</coordinates></Point>
  </Placemark>
  <Placemark>
    <name>The Wilhelm Weidner Homestead</name>
    <description><![CDATA[dead end of Angel Trail at intersection of Bulverde Rd. and US 281<br/><br/><b>Address:</b> 300200 US Highway 281 N., New Braunfels<br/><br/><b>Marker Text:</b> Using stone quarried in Cibolo Creek bed, cedar from the nearby Kramme farm, and locally-made cypress shingles and lumber, Wilhelm Weidner (1835 - 1907) copied his ancestral home in Germany in building his two-story home here in 1873-1875. He incorporated a log house owned by his wife Maria (Kramme), for more room. He also built (1870s) the smokehouse-shop-laundry and (1904) the small stone dwelling. Four generations of the Weidner family have lived hre. RTHL - 1974]]></description>
    <Point><coordinates>-98.437358,29.728635,0</coordinates></Point>
  </Placemark>
  <Placemark>
    <name>Ullrich Home</name>
    <description><![CDATA[Medallion reported stolen September 2018<br/><br/><b>Address:</b> 554 W. Mill Street, New Braunfels<br/><br/><b>Marker Text:</b> Sand brick home built 1835, by Geo. Ullrich, who had driven first wagon of German emigration Co. settlers in 1845 across the Guadalupe River. Recorded Texas Historic Landmark-1965]]></description>
    <Point><coordinates>-98.129681,29.69961,0</coordinates></Point>
  </Placemark>
